post_text:
Grab-n-Go Meals at Student Orientation
Mt. Healthy City Schools Food Service Dept
Stop by the cafeteria to pick up student lunch cards and 5 days' worth of breakfast and lunch meals!

Must be attending orientation that day to receive meals and lunch card. The student can receive 5 days' worth of meals during the student orientation period (8/20-9/4).

Lunch cards will now be REQUIRED to receive your Grab-n-Go meals during the 20-21 school year.

Please be sure to stop by the cafeteria to get more information on our meal distribution for this year and to pick up your child's lunch card. This card will be required to be able to get meals for this school year! Please keep this in a safe place.

post_text:
Mt. Healthy City School District Board of Education and Superintendent made the decision to start the 2020/2021 school year remotely. All students will be provided with Chrome books and internet access if needed. Students will have a schedule each day that includes interacting with their teachers. If students are not able to log in during class time the lessons will be recorded for review at a later time. Each student and their family will have an orientation to ensure that they are ready for the remote format. The district will re-evaluate the remote learning at the end of September.
Please visit the website or see other posts to register for Parent Orientation beginning on August 20.

post_text: Happy Friday! We want to share an update with our community. In grades K-12 over 40% of all students chose remote learning. This will allow us to bring back the remaining students in grades K-12 Monday - Friday each week. We are working on class lists now and plan to send out that information soon. The first day of school for students is 8/20/20. Parents still have the option for their students to participate in 100% remote learning for a semester or all of the 20/21 school year.

There have been several people that have shared they have not been able to open the survey. We have tried to find the reason that some can complete the survey and others are having issues. There does not seem to be a clear answer in how to make sure that everyone can open the survey. Here are two options for our families:
1. We are resharing a new link to the survey:
https://forms.gle/9EHYAyyWww7p3QKRA
2. If you have any problem with the new link please send a private message to Valerie Hawkins (superintendent at Mt. Healthy City Schools). Include your name, your address and phone number, the names of your children, grade level for 20/21 and your preference for inperson learning or remote learning. I will go in and personally enter the responses for your family.

I aplogize for the frustration that you have experienced in trying to help us get information on you preference for next year. Thank you for your continued patience.

Valerie Hawkins

post_text: Mt. Healthy CSD students and Families: Mt. Healthy Families: We know that storms in the Mt. Healthy and Springfield Twp communities were rather strong last night, and experienced or are experiencing power outages. We realize this, in addition to having to stay at home, may create extra challenges for you and your families. We are thinking about you and want you to know we'll all get through this together! Please continue to stay strong and stay at home since there are many power lines down and trees blocking sidewalks and roadways. If you have been affected by storm damage, please reach out to building principals or district administration through emails. We will try to help if we can or put you in touch with those who might be able to help you. We miss all of our students and families and hope to see all of you soon! STAY SAFE!

Students in grades 7 – 12 ONLY.

Final Chromebook pickup will be on

Monday, March 23. 10am to 12pm & 5pm to 7pm

@ Junior/Senior High Event Entrance

It will be a Drive Thru Pickup. You will stay in your car as we deliver your child’s Chromebook to you-1 per family.

If you already have a device at home that your child can use to do their remote learning, please do not come to pick up a Chromebook.

Please make sure your child is checking their Google Classroom for assignments. Teachers are assigning and grading work during these three weeks that the Governor has closed all Ohio Schools.

Fill out this survey as we collect more information:

https://forms.gle/SSJ7Am7uPNkNrCiC9

February 21 at 9:20 PM ·

We've had the busiest February! THANK YOU to our amazing presenters this month: Cincinnati State Business Technologies Division chair David Hensley, Kyle and Joe from Hamilton County, Ohio Board of Elections's Youth at the Booth, Rosemary from Rosemary's Babies Co., Jalen Alford - the youngest City of Cincinnati City Council candidate, Amy from ArtWorks Cincinnati AND Taylor and Liz from Mount St. Joseph University! post_text: Come see the show tonight! Our Choir sounds AMAZING and P. Ann Everson is outstanding!
shared_text:
ArtsConnect Springfield Township
November 8, 2019 at 11:49 AM ·

Over the past week we have been working with the staff and students of Mt Healthy City Schools to bring the community a collaborative show - Iconic Ladies of Motown. The school bells seem so much shorter when you are trying to pack rehearsals and cues into one hour! We can’t say enough about the students and staff at Mt Healthy. Collaboration is not easy. It takes listening, understanding, give and take. ArtsConnect is so grateful for this opportunity to work so closely with the Mt Healthy faculty and artist P.￼￼ Ann Everson- Price. They have given so much of themselves to this show. I encourage you to support them tonight. The show begins at 7pm. Tickets at the door, $15. Learn the history behind the music of some of Motown’s finest! Special thank you to Everett Moore, Josh Stubenvoll, Mike Kunz and Missy Knight for your time, care and expertise. ArtsWave, Ohio Arts Council

post_text:
It's Homecoming Parade Day! Hope to see you on the route cheering on our students!
Bob Suer is the Grand Marshall for the Mt. Healthy City School District Homecoming Parade. He has been a long-time supporter of the district for more than 20 years. He began BINGO for the Athletic Booster and worked it for 20 years. He was also instrumental in raising money for the new athletic facilities about 10 years ago. Bob has coached Mt. Healthy baseball for several years in addition to his involvement in the Cincinnati Red’s Community Fund. He continues to volunteer within the school and community to support our student-athletes.
Additionally, Bob raised his three nephews who attended Mt. Healthy City Schools. He recently retired from the Honeywell Corporation and now spends his time volunteering and singing for Trinity Lutheran Church Choir.

post_text: AMAZING! Thank you Owl Dads for all you do for your kids!
shared_text:
Derick J. Allen is with Ellaina M. Allen at Mt Healthy City Schools.
September 19, 2019 at 5:02 PM · Mount Healthy, OH ·

I had the privilege and honor to participate in the annual Fathers Walk Your Students to School Day. It was awesome to see so many fathers take time to spend the morning with their kids. We as both men and fathers need to intentionally develop and pour into our children. They need to know that we care and that we're here for them. Serenity and Jeremiah, I love you and will do my best to give you everything that I have.

High School students ONLY are being release due to a power outage at the Jr/Sr High School. While there is a generator, a power outage has created some issues with preparing lunches, so Mt. Healthy High School students will be released today at 11:30 am. Jr High students will remain at the school, will be fed lunch, and dismiss normally.

Additionally, phones at the Jr/Sr High School and District Office are not working due to the power outage. We appreciate your patience and understanding. Duke Energy is working to correct the issues.

We are so proud of Monica, Craig, O’lina and Shamariyah for the ways they level up every day to show the world who they are. Here they are with their medals and award certificates, and with the entire group of honorees from across the state and our Ohio TRIO president Vicki Ampiaw-Davis. Congratulations to all! #trioworks

post_text:
LOCAL12 news is having some technical issues, so some of our parents who have signed up for text alerts just got an alert that we are closed, and then it was changed to that we are on a two hour delay.

They are working to figure out the issue and are making announcements on their station and news to let folks know that it was a glitch. We are not the only District that they are incorrectly sending out alerts for, and they apologize for any inconvenience.

WE ARE IN SCHOOL TODAY! Jan 9, 2019.

shared_text:
Springfield Township
December 1, 2018 at 2:58 PM ·

With the steady rain, ArtsConnect and Township staff made the decision early to cancel the parade and outdoor student performances in the Winter Village, but this does not cancel the rest of the amazing activities at WinterFest today. Families can still look forward to the winter village being open - with food, photos with Santa, hair painting and tattoos, crafts and more! (no hay rides unless it clears up or petting zoo). LOTS of indoor activities to enjoy! Art/Craft/Vendor Fair 1-6pm, Cincinnati Civic Orchestra 1-3pm, Madcap Puppets 4:30 p.m, The Cincinnati Opera 4-6pm (15 min shows). We will make the decision on the fireworks later today. Please stay tuned!

post_text:
Important statement from Dr. Cosby, Superintendent:
An incident occurred on Thursday, February 22, 2018, that caused Mt. Healthy and Springfield Township Police Departments to respond to a possible report of a threat at Mt. Healthy Jr/Sr High School. The report and threat were unfounded and not credible. At no time were any students or staff in danger. The situation was handled appropriately, and the police are managing the case. We have security measures in place to protect students and staff; these security policies were followed and worked as they should. Providing a safe and secure learning environment is of top priority to Mt. Healthy City Schools, and we take incidents very seriously. We highly encourage parents/guardians to speak with your child(ren) about the importance of school safety and being careful of what they say through social media. Working together we can maintain an environment where students are free to focus on learning. We continue to encourage if you see something, say something or if you hear something, say something!

An incident occurred on Thursday, February 22, 2018, that caused Mt. Healthy and Springfield Township Police Departments to respond to a possible report of a threat at Mt. Healthy Jr/Sr High School. The report and threat were unfounded and not credible. At no time were any students or staff in danger. The situation was handled appropriately, and the police are managing the case. We have security measures in place to protect students and staff; these security policies were followed and worked as they should. Providing a safe and secure learning environment is of top priority to Mt. Healthy City Schools, and we take incidents very seriously. We highly encourage parents/guardians to speak with your child(ren) about the importance of school safety and being careful of what they say through social media. Working together we can maintain an environment where students are free to focus on learning. We continue to encourage if you see something, say something or if you hear something, say something!
